# Administer moth from the terminal

The `moth` binary doubles as a remote client, kubectl-style: thin wrappers
over the same `moth.admin.v1` RPCs the admin SPA uses, so the two surfaces
never diverge in capability. Everything below works without a browser.

## Contexts & authentication

Named contexts (server URL + personal access token) live in
`~/.config/moth/config.toml` (`$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/moth/config.toml` when
set); switch with `--context <name>` or `MOTH_CONTEXT=<name>`:

```toml
current-context = "prod"

[contexts.prod]
url = "{{.Endpoint}}"
token = "moth_pat_..."
```

Create a context by logging in (prompts for a personal access token â€”
mint one in the admin SPA under Account, or with `moth admin token`
locally on the server host):

```sh
moth login {{.Endpoint}}
```

PATs are revocable server-side at any time; a revoked or expired token
makes every command fail with `unauthenticated` â€” mint a new one and
re-run `moth login`. Treat `moth_pat_...` values as secrets.

## Scripting contract

- `--json` on every command: parseable output (protojson field names,
  e.g. `publishableKey`) on **stdout**, nothing else on stdout.
- Errors go to **stderr**; the exit code is non-zero on any failure.
- Destructive commands prompt; pass `--yes` in scripts.
- Secrets are redacted unless `--show-secret` is passed; keys returned
  exactly once (project creation, secret regeneration) print once and are
  never retrievable again.

## Command groups

```sh
moth project create|list|get|update|delete        # projects (one per app)
moth project keys show|reset-signing|regenerate-secret
moth project dump|apply                           # declarative state (below)
moth project export|import                        # users-JSON data lifecycle
moth user list|get|create|invite|disable|enable|delete  # end users of one project
moth user claims set / moth user sessions revoke
moth stats get                                    # analytics
moth instance get|smtp                            # instance settings incl. SMTP test
moth setup google|apple --project <slug>          # provider consoles (see provider-setup.md)
moth doctor --project <slug>                      # config health check
moth skill export                                 # this skill
```

`moth <group> --help` lists the exact flags; the full generated reference
ships in the repo under `docs/cli/`.

## Declarative projects (dump / apply)

`moth project dump <slug>` emits the project's full desired state
(settings, providers, theme, legal links) as a `ProjectSpec` YAML
document; `moth project apply -f moth.yaml` idempotently
creates-or-updates the project the spec's `slug` names. Apply twice â†’
second run reports zero changes. Version the file next to your app code.

```yaml
name: {{.ProjectName}}
slug: {{.Slug}}
settings:
  passwordMinLength: 8
  allowPublicSignup: true
  requireEmailVerification: true
  google:
    enabled: {{if .Google.Enabled}}true{{else}}false{{end}}
    webClientId: "{{if .Google.WebClientID}}{{.Google.WebClientID}}{{else}}....apps.googleusercontent.com{{end}}"
  apple:
    enabled: {{if .Apple.Enabled}}true{{else}}false{{end}}
```

Write-only secrets (Google web client secret, Apple `.p8` key) never
appear in dumps and are kept unchanged when the applied spec omits or
empties them â€” a dumpâ†’apply round trip is always safe.

## Diagnosis

```sh
moth doctor --project {{.Slug}}
```

Checks and clearly reports: JWKS reachability, SMTP (test send), provider
configs (Apple key validity/expiry, Google client IDs resolve), the pub
endpoint serving the SDK, base-URL/TLS sanity. Run it first whenever
"login stopped working".

## Typical flows

```sh
# New app, end to end
moth login {{.Endpoint}}
moth project create "My App"
moth setup google --project my-app
moth setup apple --project my-app
moth doctor --project my-app

# Read values for an integration (parse the JSON)
moth project get {{.Slug}} --json
moth project keys show {{.Slug}} --json   # JWKS URL, issuer, audience

# User support
moth user list --project {{.Slug}} --json
moth user sessions revoke <user-id-or-email> --project {{.Slug}} --yes
```
